      <p>Ordering &amp; consensus — gossip-about-gossip and virtual voting produce canonical order</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Crystallite</h3>
      <p>Execution / apply — deterministic state transitions across parallel lanes</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Lithification</h3>
      <p>Proofs / checkpoints — anchors, receipts, and finalized surfaces</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Cali</h3>
      <p>Monitoring / recovery — watchdogs, restart tooling, and health signals</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Alluvium: Data Availability &amp; Batching</h2>
  <p>
    Alluvium solves data availability before ordering even begins:
  </p>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>DAG Structure</h3>
    <pre><code>struct Certificate {'{'}
    round: u64,
    author: ValidatorId,
    transactions: Vec&lt;Transaction&gt;,
    parents: Vec&lt;CertificateHash&gt;,  // References to previous round
    signature: AggregateSignature,
{'}'}</code></pre>
    <p>Each validator creates certificates referencing certificates from the previous round, forming a directed acyclic graph.</p>
  </div>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Parallel propagation:</strong> All validators broadcast simultaneously, not sequentially</li>
    <li><strong>Erasure coding:</strong> Reed-Solomon encoding ensures any 2f+1 nodes can reconstruct data</li>
    <li><strong>Causal ordering:</strong> DAG structure naturally captures happened-before relationships</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tephra: Ordering &amp; Consensus</h2>
  <p>
    Once batches are widely available, Tephra commits a canonical global ordering:
  </p>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>Deterministic Commit Rules</h3>
    <pre><code>// Crystallite commit logic (conceptual)
fn commit(dag: &amp;Dag) -&gt; Vec&lt;CommittedSubDag&gt; {'{'}
    // Structural rules select a canonical order from available DAG vertices.
    // Output is deterministic across honest replicas.
    linearize(dag)
{'}'}</code></pre>
    <p>Commit rules produce a canonical ordering sequence without relying on a single leader to dictate order.</p>
  </div>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Leaderless ordering:</strong> Commit rules select an unambiguous sequence</li>
    <li><strong>Canonical output:</strong> The committed sequence is the ordering source of truth</li>
    <li><strong>Byzantine-resilient:</strong> Safety holds under adversarial behavior; liveness resumes when the network can make progress</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Crystallite: Deterministic Execution</h2>
  <p>
    After ordering, Crystallite executes transactions across parallel lanes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>WASM runtime:</strong> Sandboxed, metered execution of smart contracts</li>
    <li><strong>Parallel execution:</strong> Non-conflicting transactions execute concurrently</li>
    <li><strong>Merkle state:</strong> Efficient state proofs for light clients</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>Execution Pipeline</h3>
    <pre><code>fn execute_block(block: OrderedBlock) -&gt; StateRoot {'{'}
    let schedule = analyze_dependencies(&amp;block.transactions);
    let results = parallel_execute(schedule);
    update_merkle_tree(results)
{'}'}</code></pre>
    <p>Dependency analysis enables safe parallel execution without conflicts.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Lithification: Proofs &amp; Checkpoints</h2>
  <p>
    Lithification packages the applied result into anchors, certificates, and replay-friendly checkpoints.
    It converts finalized state into portable proof surfaces.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Certificates as proofs:</strong> Finality certificates are cryptographic proofs for monitoring and auditing, not gates</li>
    <li><strong>Checkpoint anchors:</strong> Lineations provide replay and sync boundaries</li>
    <li><strong>Recovery support:</strong> Finalized checkpoints simplify pruning, bootstrap, and restart flows</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cali: Monitoring &amp; Recovery</h2>
  <p>
    Cali watches the finalized chain, tracks liveness, and helps the network recover cleanly when conditions deteriorate.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Health tracking:</strong> Detects stalls, divergence, and degraded peers</li>
    <li><strong>Watchdog behavior:</strong> Supports operator visibility and automated responses</li>
    <li><strong>Restart safety:</strong> Uses anchors and checkpoints to keep recovery clean</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Lineations: Periodic Anchors</h2>
  <p>
    Every ~10 minutes, the network creates a lineation (a periodic chain anchor):
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>State snapshot:</strong> Full Merkle root of all account states</li>
    <li><strong>Validator set update:</strong> New validator weights take effect</li>
    <li><strong>Pruning point:</strong> Historical data before this can be safely archived</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h3>Why Lineations Matter</h3>
    <p>
      Light clients can sync from any lineation, not from genesis. New nodes bootstrap in minutes, not days.
    </p>
  </div>

